In this scene we have Phaedria giving orders to his servant Par-'- meno about the Eunuch and Ethiopian girl, which he intended to senff as a present to Thais. After recommending this to himin the warmest manner, he proposes to go into the country, where he would remain till the two days, agreed upon between him and Thais, were expired. Parmeno, who was no stranger to his weakness in this respect, and knew how little he was able to keep such a resolution, freely tells him his mind. Phaedria, conscious that there was good reason to suspect his steadiness, confirms himself‘ in his first resolution, and to shew Parmeno that he was still able to exert the man when he pleased.. departs, firmly purposing to remain in the country for three whole days.
